    "content": "**CONFIRM** -- context-dependent, both acceptable.\n\nBrief reasoning: 虚无 does different philosophical work in different passages. When the author discusses 虚无主义 (nihilism) and the collapse of metaphysical value hierarchies, \"nothingness\" is the right choice -- it captures the absence that follows the loss of 终极实在 (ultimate reality). When 虚无 appears in more ontological/cosmological contexts as the condition prior to or beneath all determination, \"the void\" better conveys spatial/structural emptiness without the nihilistic connotation.\n\nForcing a single default would flatten a real distinction in the author's usage. The translator needs the freedom to choose.\n\nAnd yes -- \"emptiness\" must be reserved for 空/sunyata. Non-negotiable."
